0":"1530","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6 September 1483","30 Apr 1463":"30 April 1463","June 1472":"June 1472","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Bengeworth, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Clovelly, Torridge district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Clovelly, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ciardha</b>, a midland surname meaning ‘descendant of <i>Ciardha</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>ciar</i> ‘dark, black’. See   Kerry  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhiachra</b> ‘son of <i>Fiachra</i>’.","English: from Carey Barton in Devon or Castle Cary, Lytes Cary, Cary Fitzpaine, or Babcary, all in Somerset, named for the rivers on which they stand; both river names probably derive from the Celtic root <i>car-</i> ‘love, liking’, perhaps with the meaning ‘pleasant stream’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cary","meanings":["Irish (Donegal and Westmeath) and English: variant of   Carey  .","French: variant of   Carry   2."]},{"name":"Carie","meanings":["Scottish form of Irish   Carey  ."]},{"name":"Karey","meanings":["English (London) and Irish: variant of   Carey  ."]},{"name":"Kary","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Carey  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Keary","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ciardha</b> (from a personal name based on <i>ciar</i> ‘black’), sometimes Anglicized as   Carey  ."]},{"name":"Kerry","meanings":["English: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Kari</i> (Old Norse <i>Kári</i>).","Irish: from <b>Ó Ciardha</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Ciardha</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘the black one’."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Kelly","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally an Anglicized form of the ancient Irish male name Ceallach . It is now very widely used in the English-speaking world, mainly as a girl's name. This is a transferred use of the surname <i>Ó Ceallaigh</i> ‘descendant of Ceallach’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelley","meanings":["Originally an Anglicized form of the ancient Irish male name Ceallach . It is now very widely used in the English-speaking world, mainly as a girl's name. This is a transferred use of the surname <i>Ó Ceallaigh</i> ‘descendant of Ceallach’."]},{"name":"Kellie","meanings":["Originally an Anglicized form of the ancient Irish male name Ceallach . It is now very widely used in the English-speaking world, mainly as a girl's name. This is a transferred use of the surname <i>Ó Ceallaigh</i> ‘descendant of Ceallach’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":18,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice Kelly Carey was born in 1437, in Clovelly, Devon, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thomas Carey. She married Sir Richard Weeks on 30 April 1463, in Honeychurch, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1530, in England, at the age of 93."},"et":{"1437–1530":"1437–1530","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1472–1521":"1472–1521","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1437":"1437","11 March 1521":"11. märts 1521","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","1530":"1530","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1483":"1483","6 September 1483":"6. september 1483","30 Apr 1463":"30. aprill 1463","June 1472":"juuni 1472","Honey Church, Devon, England":"Honeychurch, Devon, England","Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Holme-on-Spalding-Moor, Yorkshire, England","Bengeworth, Wychavon district, Worcestershire, England, United Kingd